I'm raising funds for Macmillan Cancer Support, who provide fantastic support to families and friends of people with cancer. In a year when Covid 19 has taken the world over, it's become even more important to support and protect those experiencing cancer, and their families and friends.

story:
Catherine Williams my beautiful best friend, sadly lost her battle with a brain tumour on Tuesday 1st December. She slipped away peacefully in her sleep. 

My world will never be same

Catherine spent her final few weeks being cared for at home by her beautiful family  and  support  bubble of carers &  nurses. I was so very privileged  to form part of this bubble along with close friend Marie.

Mary, Andy and the Boys wish to raise money  for the Macmillan’s nurses who came in every day to help care for Catherine at home and support the family. 

All donations will be greatly appreciated, 

Catherine’s funeral will take place at 11am, Saturday 19th December at Peel Green Crematorium.

pageSummaryWhat: Raising money for people battling cancer
pageSummaryWhy: my mum beat cancer thanks to macmillan
story:
In 2013, my mum was diagnosed with cancer, on top of her other medical conditions like M.E. (chronic fatigue syndrome) and colitis, our family was very scared for her life; battling cancer alone is always challenging in many ways, let alone having cancer and a physical disability. Nonetheless, words cannot describe how thankful I am to God, the Macmillan nurses who looked after her day and night and the amazing doctor's and surgeons who together saved my mum's life. 

This year, I have decided to do a sponsored Half Marathon (21KM) on the 21st of December sponsored by Macmillan, so that they can help save as many people who have been diagnosed with cancer. I aim to raise £500 for this cause; please support me through donations and shares/reposts, the link in my bio will take you to my fundraiser page - every donation is welcome! Equally, sharing this post to get as many people as possible involved is also a huge help! I'm sure that together we can smash this, I would love as many people as possible to be a part of this event!

for any further inquiries don't hesitate to get in touch:

Instagram - jovankrstic27

Email: krsticjovan2002@gmail.com

story:
I am just your average gamer trying to do my part during these tough times. With all the uncertainty with the current pandemic, charities are amongst the hardest hit. I have decided to take part in Macmillan Game Heroes 24 gaming marathon to help spread awareness, at the same time donate some money to a cause close to me.

My stream will consist of me playing various games on the PS4 that I will be playing with friends. A game that will definitely be played during the stream is Call of Duty Warzone. To make more challenging and entertaining, I will be open to any challenges that my viewers request during the stream on various games. If I manage to complete these challenges I will donate more. Example of these challenges could consist of using a certain type of Warzone Loadout class and win a game. As mentioned, I will be open to viewer challenge suggestions depending on the game I play. I will be starting the stream at 9am Saturday 12th December for 24 hours.

To sum up, hope you enjoy the stream and enjoy me raging to raise some money!
Feel free to join and keep me company, as I will definitely need it lol.

story:
Hello there!

I'm going to do a 24 hour long marathon of gaming to help raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support, a charity that helped my family and me through a really tough time this year in which my Dad lost his battle to cancer.

I'm going to be live streaming the whole thing via Twitch so you can check in to make sure I'm still awake and give me some support. I'll be joined by my friends too, so it shouldn't be boring.

In the past, I've released music and donated all the proceeds to this charity, and I recently went sober for October and in total we raised over £400. I'm raising the bar high with this one at £240, so thats £10 an hour. If we can do that, I'd be over the moon.
Thanks for reading this and...Merry Christmas!!!

pageSummary: shaving my head because Connie having Ewing Sarcoma
story:
As most of you probably know, my
sister, Connie has recently been diagnosed with Ewing Sarcoma, a rare type of
cancer that affects the bones and the surrounding tissue. In a couple of weeks,
she’ll be starting chemo – with the possibility of further radiotherapy treatment,
and in time she will have her femur replaced.

As this particular disease is usually
found in children, I am going to shave my head and donate my hair to children who
have lost their hair due to cancer treatments https://www.littleprincesses.org.uk/.
It would also be super appreciated if you could donate anything, you could offer
to  https://www.macmillan.org.uk/  – as this is such a rare type of cancer – that
would be fab!
title: Morgan shaving my head - cancer Research

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
This is the time of year when St John Ambulance would be taking Santa's floar around Kidlington to raise much needed funds. 


Sadly, we can't this Christmas and we have struggled to raise money to help buy the equipment and kit we need. I lit up the house 2 years ago and raised £330 - so here we are again, with a target of £1000! 

It may seem a bit mad, but it's just what the doctor ordered.

pageSummary: Raising money because it was the charity closest to Sue’s heart
pageSummaryWhy: it was the charity closest to Sue’s heart
story:
Mum was a kind, loving, bubbly person that wanted to help as many people as possible where ever she was able too.

She touched the lives of so many people in so many different ways as we have found out over the last month with the tremendous amount of love and support we have received.

The British heart foundation has always been the charity mum has closely supported due to her family history of heart problems and therefore we feel if anyone would like to donate on her behalf then this is where she would want the money to go.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!


Year three are skipping a mile around the school grounds to raise money for their chosen charity. They have researched into healthy hearts and had a meeting with the British Heart Foundation fund-raising manager for Rotherham. They are very passionate about making a difference.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Since April 2020, during the first lockdown I developed a huge passion for running after many years of me saying 'I hate running"- the truth is I always struggled at running! I watched one of my closest friends, progress and achieve so much in this sport and guaranteed a place in the London Marathon. For anyone who knows me, I am extremely competitive and thought right, I want to do the exact same and I want a place in the London Marathon. That was the dream! 

I am extremely lucky and privileged to have  secured a place for London Marathon 4th October 2021 for the charity Guide Dogs. The reason why I wanted to fundraise for this amazing cause is because guide dogs play a vital role in helping those who are visually inpaired.

Despite the devastation caused by loss of sight, 70% of adults receive no support within the first 12 months of diagnosis, and are likely to encounter poor education, high unemployment, depression, loneliness and financial insecurity throughout their lifetime. Childhood sight loss is on the increase. There are around 35,000 children and young people living with a vision impairment in the UK. Some 80% of a child’s learning takes place using vision, and every day they go without support can affect their development.

In 2018, it cost around £63,000 to breed, train and support a guide dog from birth to retirement, however, the cost of a guide dog is impacted not just by the cost of breeding and training, but also the cost of all of our support functions for the partnership over an average of seven years, as well as external support such as food and vets’ bills. A guide dog owner may have as many as eight guide dogs in their lifetime bringing the total cost to around £500,000.

On a daily basis we take our eye sight for granted and the thought will never cross our minds that one day we may occur serious problems with our vision. If you have a serious visual impairment, a guide dog can help you become more independent and mobile. Highly trained to support you in navigating any mobility challenges you may face, guide dogs are a great way to get you out and about with confidence.

I would really appreciate any donation for this great cause, nothing is too small, please help me raise my target of £2000 and I will promise to complete that finishing line in style!

Thank you in advance for all your support.


Hayley/DJ Hailz
title: Hayley running for Guide Dogs!

pageSummary: Raise money for Cancer Research because It is a charity near to my heart
pageSummaryWhy: It is a charity near to my heart
story: My sister Sally was diagnosed with Bowel and Breast Cancer at the same time, it was a double blow for her. She is inspirational, kind and never thinks of herself and fought everyday. Everyone involved in her care, the nurses, Doctors and all the other healthcare professionals were amazing, they were caring, there by her side and helped, encourage her every step. With an amazing husband and family who are so proud of her she was able this year to do the London marathon with her daughter in law. Cancer Research continues to look at better treatments and need all our donations, please help me to help people like my sister Sally who is my inspiration to recover, get better and live her life a day at a time. I had my head shaved and am proud to do this for every cancer person who needs Cancer Research to continue their amazing work. Thank you Wendy

pageSummary: Howard Lawrence and Mark Innes road trip.
pageSummaryWhat: Howard Lawrence and Mark Innes road trip.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Most of us have lost someone close to the evil of Cancer. This tour is a tribute to the loved ones we’ve lost and those suffering a long fight to beat it. Cancer has taken loved ones from both of our families. So, on May 1st Mark Innes and I are riding our motorcycles around the whole coast of mainland U.K. it’s going to take 31 days and we will cover approximately 4600 miles. Hopefully we will raise awareness and donations in achieving this epic road trip. This is in memory of our loved ones taken too soon. Anne, Ross, Marcia, Les, Val, Mick and Audrey.
Lastly for John, who’s still very much with us, battling this terrible disease.
Please give what you can. Thank you.

pageSummary: Patagonia Trek November 2021 because they provide amazing support and end of life care
pageSummaryWhy: they provide amazing support and end of life care
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

2020 has been a tough year for many and the support of organisations like Marie Curie is so important for individuals and families in need of support with end of life care, and at times of bereavement.  To keep this support available for all those who need it, the charity needs to keep raising vital funds.  

We are therefore aiming to raise £8,000 by undertaking a trek in Patagonia in November 2021.  We will spend a week following the trail of Welsh settlers who established the colony in 1865 when around 160 people from various parts of Wales sailed from Liverpool aboard the Mimosa. They settled in the Chubut Valley in Southern Argentina, where a culturally vibrant Welsh-Argentinian population still thrives today in the heart of Patagonia. The trek will start in Esquel and we will walk up to 26 k per day with beautiful views of the Andes to keep us going, passing through places like Nant Y Pysgod and Cwm Hyfryd, and eventually arriving in the town of Trevelin.

This is a fantastic cause so we will be so grateful for any donations that you can give.  We will be running all sorts of different activities over the next 12-months so there will be lots of opportunities to get involved.

Thank you!

Gareth and Alys Petty

pageSummary: Big Winter Wander WWF 24TH JANUARY 2021 because Our Wildlife and Nature needs us.
pageSummaryWhy: Our Wildlife and Nature needs us.
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.  Please check in on our progress and updates. 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummaryWhat: We are fundraising to protect nature
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY you might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That's because half of all UK species are in decline. We're losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in WWF/Grow Community's Big Winter Wander Activity Trail between 23rd and 31st January 2021, you and your family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now it's our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
charity.registrationNumber: 1072612 (England & Wales) and SC043677 (Scotland)
pageSummary: I am running the Royal Parks Half Marathon because they make a stand for children's rights and health
pageSummaryWhat: I am running the Royal Parks Half Marathon
pageSummaryWhy: they make a stand for children's rights and health
story:
I'm running the 2020 Royal Parks Half Marathon. I will be fundraising for Unicef. Unicef needs your help to support children around the world. Your donation will help to provide children life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection. Help me smash their fundraising targets and help children worldwide. Your donation will make a difference.

I love running! And I want to make a difference. Running is extremely good for my mental and physical health and I want it to have some good for others' health as well.

Please donate what ever you can to my fundraiser for Unicef UK. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. Thank you
title: Pete's raising money for Unicef

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
pageSummary: We are fundraising because we care and we can
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good. 

Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in climate-vulnerable communities.
title: BwithuU WaterAid Appeal 2021
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
media.images.image.caption: NA

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
